Lag Selection Criteria Explained

| Criterion | Full Form                          | Purpose                                           | Rule                 |
| --------- | ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | -------------------- |
| AIC       | Akaike Information Criterion       | Finds the best balance between fit and complexity | Lowest value is best |
| BIC       | Bayesian Information Criterion     | Penalizes complex models more strongly            | Lowest value is best |
| HQIC      | Hannan-Quinn Information Criterion | Middle ground between AIC and BIC                 | Lowest value is best |
| FPE       | Final Prediction Error             | Estimates future forecasting error                | Lowest value is best |

=======
1. AIC (Akaike Information Criterion)
What is it?

AIC checks:

"Does adding more lags improve prediction accuracy?"

Formula:

AIC = -2(Log Likelihood) + 2k

Where:

Log Likelihood = Model fit quality
k = Number of parameters
Use
Focuses on prediction accuracy
Often chooses larger lag values
Preferred when forecasting is the main goal
Your Result
Lag	AIC
15	46.97 ⭐

Therefore:

✅ AIC selected VAR(15)

2. BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion)
What is it?

BIC is similar to AIC but penalizes complexity more heavily.

Formula:

BIC = -2(Log Likelihood) + k ln(n)

Where:

n = Number of observations
Use
Avoids overfitting
Produces simpler models
Often selects smaller lags
Your Result
Lag	BIC
10	47.27 ⭐

Therefore:

✅ BIC selected VAR(10)

3. HQIC (Hannan-Quinn Information Criterion)
What is it?

HQIC is a compromise between AIC and BIC.

Use
More balanced
Neither too simple nor too complex
Your Result
Lag	HQIC
15	47.09 ⭐

Therefore:

✅ HQIC selected VAR(15)

4. FPE (Final Prediction Error)
What is it?

FPE estimates how much forecasting error the model will produce on unseen data.

Use
Directly related to forecasting quality
Lower value means better future predictions
